# Kaseki Agent API Service - Environment Configuration Example
# 
# Copy this file to .env and update values for your deployment:
#   cp .env.example .env
#   # Edit .env with your actual values
#   docker-compose up -d
#
# SECURITY: Secrets are stored in host-based files, NOT in .env
# See "REQUIRED: Secret Files" section below for setup instructions

# ===== REQUIRED: Secret Files (NOT in .env) =====

# Kaseki Agent reads secrets from host filesystem locations:
#   Primary: /agents/secrets/{secret-name}
#   Fallback: ~/secrets/{secret-name}
#
# Required secret files (create these on your host):
#
# 1. OpenRouter API Key (for Pi agent invocation)
#    File: /agents/secrets/openrouter_api_key
#    Content: Your OpenRouter API key (sk-or-...)
#    Setup:
#      mkdir -p /agents/secrets
#      echo "sk-or-your-actual-key" > /agents/secrets/openrouter_api_key
#      chmod 600 /agents/secrets/openrouter_api_key
#
# 2. Kaseki API Keys (access control for API service)
#    File: /agents/secrets/kaseki_api_keys
#    Content: One API key per line (newline-separated)
#    Setup:
#      echo "sk-api-key-1" > /agents/secrets/kaseki_api_keys
#      echo "sk-api-key-2" >> /agents/secrets/kaseki_api_keys
#      chmod 600 /agents/secrets/kaseki_api_keys
#
# 3. GitHub App Credentials (optional, for PR creation)
#    Files:
#      /agents/secrets/github_app_id           (numeric App ID)
#      /agents/secrets/github_app_client_id    (OAuth Client ID)
#      /agents/secrets/github_app_private_key  (PEM-format private key)
#    Setup:
#      echo "123456" > /agents/secrets/github_app_id
#      echo "Iv1.abc..." > /agents/secrets/github_app_client_id
#      cat your-private-key.pem > /agents/secrets/github_app_private_key
#      chmod 600 /agents/secrets/github_app_*
#
# NOTE: Do NOT store secrets in this .env file. The system will reject inline
# secret environment variables (OPENROUTER_API_KEY, KASEKI_API_KEYS, etc.)
# and require them to be in files.

# ===== OPTIONAL: Docker Image Configuration =====

# Docker image to use for kaseki-agent containers
# Default: docker.io/cyanautomation/kaseki-agent:latest
# You can use a local build tag: kaseki-agent:node24-local
KASEKI_API_IMAGE=docker.io/cyanautomation/kaseki-agent:latest

# ===== OPTIONAL: API Service Configuration =====

# API service listen port
# Default: 8080
KASEKI_API_PORT=8080

# Log level for kaseki-api service
# Options: debug, info, warn, error
# Default: info
KASEKI_API_LOG_LEVEL=info

# Maximum concurrent kaseki-agent runs
# Adjust based on available system resources
# Default: 1
KASEKI_API_MAX_CONCURRENT_RUNS=1

# ===== OPTIONAL: Agent Execution Configuration =====

# Maximum time (in seconds) for a single Pi agent invocation
# Default: 3600 (60 minutes)
# Increase for larger codebases, decrease to fail fast
KASEKI_AGENT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS=3600

# Maximum allowed diff size in bytes
# Default: 400000 (400 KB)
# Prevents agents from making too many changes
KASEKI_MAX_DIFF_BYTES=400000

# ===== OPTIONAL: Container User Configuration =====

# Container user and group (UID:GID)
# IMPORTANT: Must match the Dockerfile build (UID 10000)
# Default: 10000:10000
KASEKI_CONTAINER_USER=10000:10000

# ===== OPTIONAL: Docker Socket Group =====

# Docker group ID on the host (for spawning worker containers)
# Get with: stat -c '%g' /var/run/docker.sock
# Default: 985 (common on Linux)
# On macOS/WSL, use the actual group ID from the socket
DOCKER_GID=985

# ===== OPTIONAL: User Configuration =====

# Container API user (if different from default)
# Default: 10000:10000
KASEKI_API_USER=10000:10000

# ===== OPTIONAL: Secret File Locations (Advanced) =====

# If your secret files are in non-standard locations, override these:
# (Most users should not need to change these)

# KASEKI_API_KEYS_FILE: Path to API keys file
# OPENROUTER_API_KEY_FILE: Path to OpenRouter API key file
# GITHUB_APP_ID_FILE: Path to GitHub App ID file
# GITHUB_APP_CLIENT_ID_FILE: Path to GitHub App Client ID file
# GITHUB_APP_PRIVATE_KEY_FILE: Path to GitHub App Private Key file
#
# Default locations: /agents/secrets/{name} or ~/secrets/{name}

# ===== OPTIONAL: GitHub App Authentication =====

# If using GitHub App for authenticated git operations (optional)
# Create the corresponding secret files (see "REQUIRED: Secret Files" above)
# No configuration needed here - the system will detect them automatically

# ===== SYSTEM DIRECTORIES =====

# These are usually set automatically, but can be overridden:

# Results directory (persists run artifacts)
# Default: /agents/kaseki-results
# KASEKI_RESULTS_DIR=/agents/kaseki-results

# API log directory
# Default: /var/log/kaseki-api
# KASEKI_API_LOG_DIR=/var/log/kaseki-api

# ===== DEPLOYMENT NOTES =====

# 1. Create /agents directory with proper permissions:
#    IMPORTANT: If running kaseki-agent with `sudo`, use world-writable permissions
#    because the host script runs as root and creates subdirectories that the
#    container (UID 10000) needs to write to.
#
#    sudo mkdir -p /agents/secrets
#    sudo chmod 777 /agents  # World-writable (required when using sudo)
#    
#    OR if running without sudo:
#    sudo mkdir -p /agents/secrets
#    sudo chown 10000:10000 /agents
#    sudo chmod 755 /agents

# 2. Set up secret files (see "REQUIRED: Secret Files" section above):
#    mkdir -p /agents/secrets
#    echo "sk-or-..." > /agents/secrets/openrouter_api_key
#    chmod 600 /agents/secrets/openrouter_api_key
#    echo "sk-api-..." > /agents/secrets/kaseki_api_keys
#    chmod 600 /agents/secrets/kaseki_api_keys

# 3. Ensure Docker socket is accessible:
#    export DOCKER_GID=$(stat -c '%g' /var/run/docker.sock)

# 4. For production, use a reverse proxy (nginx) for HTTPS:
#    Listen on 443 (HTTPS) and proxy to localhost:8080

# 5. Set up log rotation if logging to files:
#    sudo cp ops/logrotate/kaseki-api /etc/logrotate.d/

# 6. Monitor API health:
#    curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $KASEKI_API_KEYS" http://localhost:8080/api/health
